{"default_url":null,"content":{"state":2,"taskInstructions":"<h2>Instructions</h2><br>Identify third party SaaS providers being used. Sometimes they support federated/managed authentication without MFA.<br><br><h2>Variation: dig</h2><br>1. Use dig to query TXT records from the target domain.<br><code>dig txt domain.com +short<br></code><br><h3>Example:</h3><br><code>dig txt office.com +short<br>&quot;google-site-verification=zqthuNzyDukN37Znr1L5xdDKHo7KZUL2LTyOqzU7cFo&quot;<br>&quot;google-site-verification=WiCZ6HhPFmPMk5PTkdpSnevgiRttL2tQ-7QA_Z81JRk&quot;<br>&quot;facebook-domain-verification=h6ulkdsze2qhdtbdnivt3lilquemgc&quot;<br>&quot;google-site-verification=ntjPAtTot4dDzv9Z7WpQYYSlgVajPuBZx0FoZyRE8q8&quot;<br>&quot;google-site-verification=iJN6qYrMLZmqRE70EPwnmUtT7qW3Rs-X3_wgil1YQjw&quot;<br>&quot;google-site-verification=V6qxrpALPrk4N8F9wqgUVMwFdKi4sSUY5dLaICCx5rU&quot;<br>&quot;google-site-verification=9aqt6mNhLx_inDlQjEfPiqq_TYfy72IFpoUh5_gijEg&quot;<br></code><br>","references":[],"isTaskInstructionsVisible":true,"isCommentMandatory":false,"fields":[],"masterFinding":{"id":17065336,"exploitInstructions":"","verificationInstructions":"<h2>Instructions</h2><br>Attempt to identify service provider through analysis of TXT based domain authentication tokens.<br><br> 1. Load Resolve-DnsDomainValidationToken into the PowerShell session.<br><br><code>IEX(<b>New</b>-Object System.Net.WebClient).DownloadString(&quot;https://raw.githubusercontent.com/NetSPI/PowerShell/master/Resolve-DnsDomainValidationToken.ps1&quot;)<br></code><br>2. Run Resolve-DnsDomainValidationToken to collect and fingerprint TXT records<br><br><code>$Results = Resolve-DnsDomainValidationToken -Verbose -Domain adroll.com <br></code><br>3. View records in the console<br><br><code>$Results<br></code><br>","remediationInstructions":"Remove domain validation tokens when possible.<br>","name":"General Information - DNS TXT - Domain Validation Token","sourceId":"M:fd7fb236-0431-4b33-b5d2-01f0114e987c","severity":"Informational","businessImpact":"When domain validation tokens are not removed after being used they allow remote unauthenticated attackers to fingerprint third party services being used by the organization that could be targeted in future attacks.","description":"Domain validation tokens appear to exist in one or more DNS TXT record.  Domain validation tokens are initially used by vendors to validate ownership of domains, but can usually be removed after that validation has occurred.<br>"}}}